<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-03-03T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-03-03T09:00:00-05:00" n="432" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d432">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.943 Manchuria/53: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-03-03T22:00:00+08:00">March 3, 1938—10
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 3—1:58 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>354. Following from Tokyo.</p>
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>“March 3, 6 p.m. Reference Department’s 319, November 28, 3
                                    p.m.,<note n="94" xml:id="d432fn94"><ref target="frus1937v03#pg_941"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                            Relations</hi>, 1937, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 941</ref>.</note> extraterritoriality in
                                Manchuria.</p>
                            <pb facs="0452" n="448" xml:id="pg_448"/>
                            <p>The Foreign Minister has replied to my note of December 2 [<hi rend="italic">1?</hi>], 1937<note n="96" xml:id="d432fn96"><ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_154"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                            Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 154</ref>.</note> (see
                                despatch No. 2689 of December 9, 1937<note n="97" xml:id="d432fn97">Not printed.</note>) under date of March l.<note n="98" xml:id="d432fn98">For text, see <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_154"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                            Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 154</ref>.</note> The
                                Foreign Minister’s note in translation refers to the subject matter
                                of my note and concludes with the following paragraph. <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>‘The policy of the Government of Manchukuo in this instance,
                                        which concerns the treatment of nationals of third countries
                                        and juridical persons of third countries, is a matter in
                                        which the Japanese Government is not concerned and the
                                        Japanese Government, accordingly, regrets that it is not in
                                        a position to make any explanation’.</p>
                                </quote></p>
                            <p>Please repeat to Peiping, Hankow and to the Department as our No.
                                146, March 3, 6 p.m. Grew”.</p>
                        </quote>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>